SIMPLE: overhand
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Overhand
<hw>O"ver*hand`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The
upper hand; advantage; superiority; mastery.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He had gotten thereby a great <qex>overhand</qex> on me.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. More.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Baseball)</fld> <def>A throwing or pitching style
that is overhanded; also an overhand{2} pitch.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overhand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Overhand
<hw>O"ver*hand`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Sewing)</fld>
<def>Over and over; -- applied to a style of sewing, or to a seam, in
which two edges, usually selvages, are sewed together by passing each
stitch over both.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Baseball, Cricket, Tennis, etc.)</fld> <def>Done
(as pitching or bowling) with the hand higher than the elbow, or the arm
above, or higher than, the shoulder; <as>as, an <ex>overhand</ex> pitch;
an <ex>overhand</ex> stroke</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Overhand knot</b></col>. <cd>See <xex>Illustration</xex>
of <er>Knot</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Overhand</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Overhand
<hw>O"ver*hand`</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In an overhand manner or
style.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>overhanded</ent>⟦br⟧
